alue="734621"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018566-20180320-194945"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Changi Airport T2 to undergo major facelift; works to start 2019 and end by 2024</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SINGAPORE - Changi Airport Terminal 2 will undergo a multimillion-dollar major facelift, with works expected to start next year and end by 2024, The Straits Times has learnt.</Para><Para>The works at T2 will include a refresh of the entire facility, for example, with new check-in areas and counters so that more self-service options for passengers, such as those now available at T1, can be rolled out.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The baggage handling system will also be overhauled to allow for more automation to reduce manpower requirements, for example, to sort early check-in bags.</Para><Para>At all the other three terminals, the latest baggage systems are already in place.</Para><Para>The works are expected to increase capacity at the terminal, which can now handle about 22 million passengers a year, by another three to five million, The Straits Times understands.</Para><Para>The boost will be much needed as Changi Airport, which handled a record number 62.2 million passengers in 2017, expects to continue to grow to tap a growing demand for air travel in the region.</Para><Para>With current upgrading works at T1 and the construction of Jewel Changi Airport - a mainly commercial complex - almost completed, the plans for T2 are in line with Changi's strategy of continual upgrades and enhancements to stay ahead of rival airports. t4-shell.png Related StoryChangi Airport's Terminal 4: Take a 360-degree tour of the new 'self-service' T4 Building Terminal 5 Related StoryDecades of groundwork for T5 to take flight</Para><Para>T2 last went under the knife in 2003, with a $240 million upgrading project.</Para><Para>The works which were completed in 2006 added new commercial areas for shopping and dining, and also included the construction of a 250m long leaf-shaped glass canopy at the departure kerbside to shield travellers from sunlight and rain.</Para><Para>Lifts and escalators were also added or re-positioned.</Para><Para>Since then, the other terminals have caught up.</Para><Para>T3 opened in 2008, T4 started operating in October 2017 and the finishing touches are now being put at T1 where upgrading works started in 2014.</Para><Para>Regular traveller marketing executive Annie Lim, 38, said: "T2 is nice and good compared to many other airport terminals around the region. But when you compare it with the other terminals at Changi, it does look a bit dated and the lighting is not very good either so it looks a bit dark in places."</Para><Para>Singapore Airlines (SIA) spokesman Nicholas Ionides said the planned upgrades will improve the efficiency of the airline's operations "and create a better travel experience for our customers at Changi Airport".</Para><Para>He added that while SIA does not expect major disruptions on operations during the works, the airline will work closely with airport authorities, as well as ground handling agents and partners to ensure minimal disruption and inconvenience to customers.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Karamjit Kaur </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="c